## Building a Stopwatch in Angular

**Mental model:** Track a *start timestamp* and compute `elapsed = now - start` each tick so the timer never drifts. The component holds `elapsed` for the template; the start time and interval handle are plain fields. Classic `NgModule` setup — no signals/standalone, and no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Fields for state and plumbing
```typescript
elapsed = 0;
running = false;
laps: number[] = [];
private startTime = 0;
private handle: any = null;
```

### Step 2 — Tick from a timestamp
Use `setInterval` (~30ms) and recompute from the anchor. Resume by anchoring `now - elapsed`.

```typescript
start(): void {
  if (this.running) { return; }
  this.startTime = Date.now() - this.elapsed;
  this.running = true;
  this.handle = setInterval(() => { this.elapsed = Date.now() - this.startTime; }, 30);
}
```

### Step 3 — Stop, reset, lap
```typescript
stop(): void { this.running = false; clearInterval(this.handle); }
reset(): void { this.stop(); this.elapsed = 0; this.laps = []; }
lap(): void { this.laps.push(this.elapsed); }
```

### Step 4 — Clean up with OnDestroy
Always clear the interval when the component is torn down.

```typescript
ngOnDestroy(): void { clearInterval(this.handle); }
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Double-start | The `running` guard returns early. |
| Resume after pause | `now - elapsed` preserves elapsed time. |
| Destroy while running | `ngOnDestroy` clears the interval. |

**Interview tip:** Implementing `OnDestroy` to clear timers is the lifecycle detail interviewers look for in Angular — an un-cleared `setInterval` is a classic memory-leak gotcha.

